// Regression floor for bug #94 [P0] — calling a function-typed FIELD via a
// fused dot-call (`h.validate()`, where `validate` is a `() => ...` FIELD, not a
// method) silently no-op'd on the LLVM native backend, exit 0, no diagnostic
// (the P0.3 dropped-operation shape). Distilled from Atlantis ORM Track 06's
// boot `Db.validate()`, whose RepoHandle carries a `() => Promise<void> validate`
// field.
//
// The trigger is a NAME COLLISION, isolated here to its minimal form: some
// OTHER reachable class (`Other`) has an in-language method with the SAME name
// AND arity as the closure field (`compute(int)`). LlvmGen's by-name CallDyn
// path builds a candidate chain over every in-language method of that name and
// compares the receiver's effective classId against each; the receiver
// (`Handle`) matches none, so the chain fell through — and the field-closure
// fallback (read the field, if it holds a closure dispatch through it) was
// gated on `cands.empty()`, so a non-empty candidate set skipped it entirely
// and the call dropped into the void tail: silent no-op. Without `Other` the
// candidate set is empty and the same call always worked, which is exactly why
// the defect surfaced only in a large program (a same-name method existing
// somewhere) and hid in every minimal repro that lacked one.
//
// Fixed in src/LlvmGen.cpp (Op::CallDyn by-name path): the field-closure
// fallback now fires on ANY fallthrough where no native method covers the name,
// not only when the candidate set is empty — a fallthrough already proves the
// receiver is none of the candidate classes. Engine-neutral (oracle/IR/cpp were
// already correct); pinned here so a future dispatch change can't silently
// regress it. Non-async so it runs on all four corpus lanes.
class Handle {
    (int) => int compute;
    new Handle((int) => int compute) { this.compute = compute; }
}
class Other {
    int tag;
    new Other() { this.tag = 0; }
    int compute(int x) { return x * 100; }   // same name + arity as the field
}
void main() {
    Other o = Other();                        // forces `compute` into the candidate set
    Handle h = Handle((x) => x + 1);
    // fused field-closure dot-call, with an argument, result consumed and
    // nested inside a larger expression — all the shapes bug #94 dropped.
    console.writeln(h.compute(41).toString());
    console.writeln((h.compute(5) * 2).toString());
    var f = h.compute;                        // the documented workaround still works
    console.writeln(f(99).toString());
    console.writeln("tag=" + o.tag.toString());
}
main();
